],"burial":{"place":"Metairie Cemetery","city":"New Orleans","state":"Louisiana"},"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"family","header":"Her son accepted a Nobel Prize","body":"Her youngest son, Henry Richardson Labouisse Jr., directed UNICEF and accepted the 1965 Nobel Peace Prize on its behalf — and married Ève Curie, daughter of Marie. Frances herself was a granddaughter of Bishop-General Leonidas Polk, the “fighting bishop” of the Confederacy."},{"number":2,"category":"marriage","header":"Married Henry Richardson Labouisse, 1895 New Orleans","body":"Frances 'Fannie' Huger married Henry Richardson Labouisse Sr. on January 10, 1895 at New Orleans. They raised three sons in Louisiana: William Huger (HD2604), John Witherspoon (HD2605), and Henry Richardson Labouisse Jr. (HD2606). She lived to see Henry Jr. become a US ambassador, dying in Manhattan in 1948 at age 81 before his UNICEF tenure."}],"slug":"frances-huger-1867"}},"burialCemetery":null,"institutionsById":{"INST152":{"id":"INST152","primary_name":"Smith College","name":"Smith College","short_name":"Smith","alt_names":[],"type":"university","founding_year":1871,"location":{"city":"Northampton","state":"Massachusetts","country":"USA"},"primary_persons":[],"hooker_connected_people":["HD2616"],"person_ids":[],"related_institutions":[],"related_landmarks":[],"tags":[],"sources":[],"notes":"Smith College in Northampton MA (founded 1871). Women's liberal arts college. Hooker-descendant alumni include HD2616 Elizabeth 'Bobo' Labouisse Wright (gen 10)."}},"crossConnections":[]}